1.	Do we need all 5 layers shown in the diagram?
 Yes, conceptually we need all 5 layers—but not all need to be heavy or physical.
In the IM US DnA Hub diagram, the five layers (Sense, Aggregate, Publish, Analyze, Governance/Security) represent separation of concerns, not five separate platforms. Architecturally, this separation is required to scale safely.
•	Sense is required to isolate raw ingestion, source alignment, and data protection. Mixing raw and business-ready data creates audit, security, and quality risks.
•	Aggregate is mandatory because this is where data is integrated, conformed, and shaped into enterprise truth (Integration + DWH).
•	Publish is required to decouple business-ready data from consumption patterns. Without it, consumption tools directly hit core tables, tightly coupling analytics to storage.
•	Analyze is optional in tooling but mandatory in concept — data must be consumed somewhere (BI, DS, AI, APIs).
•	Governance & Security must exist across all layers; absence of this turns the hub into an uncontrolled data lake.
Trade off:
The trade off is added architectural discipline and initial complexity. However, collapsing layers for short term speed almost always results in long term technical debt, KPI inconsistency, and governance gaps.
Soln: Keep all 5 layers logically. Allow some layers (Publish, Semantic) to be lighter or view based, but don’t remove them.

2. Is CDM the Gold layer or the Provision layer?
CDM belongs to the Aggregate layer (Integration + DWH), NOT the Publish layer.
As per the architecture:
•	CDM is not Gold
•	CDM is not Provision
•	CDM is the foundation that Gold and Provision consume
Correct positioning:
•	CDM lives in the Aggregate layer, specifically: 
o	Snowflake Integration
o	Snowflake DWH
CDM defines:
•	Canonical business entities
•	Standard grain
•	Identifiers
•	Relationships
•	Shared attributes
Gold datasets are:
•	Use case optimized
•	Often built from CDM
•	Typically exposed via Publish
So:
CDM → Gold → Provision → Analyze
Trade off:
Placing CDM upstream means teams must align early on definitions. This slightly slows initial delivery but prevents continuous rework and reconciliation later.
Soln: Treat CDM as the enterprise backbone, Gold as optimization.

3. Do we need CDM on the Publish layer?
No — CDM should NOT live on the Publish layer. Publish should expose CDM, not redefine it.
From the diagram’s intent:
•	Aggregate layer = Truth creation
•	Publish layer = Controlled exposure
CDM should already be finalized before Publish. Publish should:
•	Expose CDM entities
•	Apply minor shaping if needed
•	Provide access control and decoupling
If CDM logic exists on Publish:
•	Business truth shifts too late
•	Semantic drift increases
•	Multiple “truths” emerge depending on consumer
Trade off:
Keeping Publish lightweight limits flexibility in Publish itself, but massively improves stability, governance, and reuse across tools.
Soln: CDM finalized in Aggregate; Publish is only an interface.
4. Is CDM a physical layer or just a view on top of Publish?
CDM is primarily physical in DWH, with optional logical extensions via views.
As per the diagram:
•	CDM is primarily physical tables in Snowflake DWH, because: 
o	Integration needs performance
o	Governance needs stable assets
o	Multiple consumers depend on consistency
However:
•	CDM may expose logical views: 
o	To simplify consumption
o	To handle evolving requirements
o	To decouple some consumers
But critically:
CDM should never be “only a view on top of Publish.”
That would mean:
•	CDM depends on consumption logic
•	Governance is downstream
•	Performance and lineage suffer
Trade off:
Physical CDM costs storage and modeling effort; view only CDM increases fragility and ambiguity.
Soln:
•	Core CDM = physical in DWH
•	Optional domain friendly views = allowed
•	Publish views ≠ CDM
5. HYD alignment and consolidation of IM DnA layers
Architect perspective (architecture based):
The IM US DnA Hub diagram represents a single logical enterprise data platform. HYD is an execution workforce operating within this platform, not parallel architecture. In the future state, alignment with HYD is required to ensure that work executed in the Aggregate layer (Snowflake Integration + DWH) and downstream does not result in duplicated integration logic, diverging curated datasets, or independently defined KPIs.
Architectural advantages:
•	Preserves the hub and spoke architecture
•	Prevents semantic and metric divergence across teams
•	Ensures governance is enforceable at one control point
Trade off / limitation:
•	Reduces local design freedom for execution teams
•	Requires stronger upfront architectural governance
•	Slightly higher coordination cost
Architect conclusion:
This trade off is intentional. Enterprise architectures optimize for long term coherence, not short term autonomy.
6. Definition of CDM and its use cases
Architect perspective (diagram based):
In the diagram, the Common Data Model (CDM) logically resides in the Aggregate layer, specifically within Snowflake Integration and Snowflake DWH. CDM is the canonical representation of business entities — HCP, Product, Territory, Interaction, Sales — defined with consistent grain, identifiers, and relationships.
CDM is not a consumption construct; it is a truth creation construct.
Architectural use cases:
•	Enables reuse across domains, brands, and analytics products
•	Acts as the stable substrate for semantic and AI ready products
•	Shields downstream tools from structural changes upstream
Trade off / limitation:
•	Requires stronger data modeling discipline
•	Introduces governance checkpoints for structural changes
Architect conclusion:
CDM transforms Integration + DWH from “data plumbing” into enterprise knowledge infrastructure.
7. Why CDM is required in this architecture
Architect perspective (diagram based):
The diagram explicitly supports multiple downstream consumers (BI, Analytics Workbench, Databricks, external access). Without CDM, each consumer path becomes a semantic boundary, causing business truth to fragment downstream. CDM centralizes semantic gravity upstream so that meaning is defined once and propagated everywhere.
Architectural advantages:
•	Single version of enterprise truth
•	Predictable lineage and auditability
•	Reduced metric reconciliation and downstream defects
Trade off / limitation:
•	Less freedom to redefine core meaning per use case
•	Requires intentional design rather than emergent modeling
Architect conclusion:
The more consumers architecture supports, the more mandatory CDM becomes.
8. CDM compared to the Gold layer
Architect perspective (diagram based):
The Gold layer lives near Publish / Analyze, optimized for usability and performance. CDM lives earlier in Aggregate, optimized for correctness and reuse. These layers solve different concerns.
•	CDM = enterprise semantics and structure
•	Gold = consumer specific optimization
Gold derives from CDM; CDM must not derive from Gold.
Architectural advantages:
•	Stable enterprise contract
•	Independent evolution of consumption patterns
•	Contained blast radius of change
Trade off / limitation:
•	Gold cannot arbitrarily redefine entities
•	Some transformations must move upstream
Architect conclusion:
CDM protects truth, Gold protects experience.
5. CDM integration with Semantic and Governance layers
(Including Business KPI / definitions location)
Architect perspective (diagram based):
The diagram shows Governance as a cross cutting layer and Semantic exposure happening through Publish.
In the future state:
•	CDM provides the physical data substrate
•	Business semantics (names, KPI logic, joins) are applied via the Semantic layer
•	KPI definitions, ownership, and certification reside in the Governance platform
Business KPIs and definitions do NOT live in:
•	ARDs
•	Gold datasets
•	BI tools
 They DO live in:
•	Governance platform (definitions, ownership, lifecycle)
•	Semantic layer (application of those definitions to CDM)
Architectural advantages:
•	One authoritative KPI definition across the enterprise
•	True separation of data, meaning, and control
•	Enables AI and automation safely
Trade off / limitation:
•	KPI changes require governance workflows
•	Experimental metrics need sandboxing strategies
Architect conclusion:
This is control plane architecture, not reporting architecture.
9. Using existing ARDs to build CDM or semantic data products
Architect perspective (diagram based):
ARDs currently exist in DWH / Publish feeding Analyze. The future state does not discard ARDs; it demotes them from “truth creators” to “truth consumers.” ARDs are aligned to CDM and incrementally refactored into semantic data products.
Architectural advantages:
•	Preserves investment
•	Enables incremental migration
•	Minimizes delivery disruption
Trade off / limitation:
•	Transitional duplication
•	Requires refactoring discipline
•	Full consistency realized over time, not instantly
Architect conclusion:
This is a controlled convergence strategy, not a big bang rewrite.






